---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  pageHeading="For Repeater Owners"
  description="You already have what the mesh needs most: elevation. Here's the minimal investment to host a backbone router."
>
  <!-- Intro -->
  <section class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
    <h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-tight text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">
      If you own a repeater site
    </h2>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      You already have the expensive part figured out: elevation.
    </p>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      $60-150 in hardware, a small solar panel, maybe 10 square feet of tower space. That's what it would take to deploy a router that bridges the KC mesh coverage gap.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The Value Proposition -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-blue/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-blue/5 to-kc-sky/10 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-kc-sky/20 dark:from-kc-blue/10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Why tower sites work so well</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Elevation is everything for UHF mesh networking.</strong> The difference between a ground-level node and a tower-mounted node isn't incremental—it's the difference between 2 miles and 20 miles of coverage.
      </p>
      <p>
        You've already got the tower, site access, power infrastructure. A Meshtastic router is completely independent—uses almost none of your resources, just happens to benefit from the elevation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-200 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">What you'd provide</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Tower mounting space (~1 sq ft)</li>
          <li>• Space for small solar panel</li>
          <li>• Occasional access for maintenance</li>
          <li>• That's it</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-200 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-kc-blue dark:text-kc-sky">What you'd get</h3>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Complementary emergency communications capability</li>
          <li>• Text coordination for public service events</li>
          <li>• Supporting local resilience infrastructure</li>
          <li>• Hosting credit for backbone node</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The West Side Priority -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-red/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-red/5 to-sunset-amber/5 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-sunset-amber/20 dark:from-kc-red/10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-kc-red dark:text-sunset-amber">The obvious gap: West side coverage</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Router 1 (east side) is operational.</strong> It's covering 5-8 miles from a residential roof. But the west side—Johnson County, Shawnee, Overland Park area—that's wide open.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>West-side deployment is the logical next step.</strong> Somewhere in western Johnson County or western KC proper. A repeater site with elevation would close this gap completely.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you've got elevation west of State Line Road, you could deploy a router that bridges the entire metro.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Hardware Requirements -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What the hardware actually looks like</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        This isn't enterprise equipment. It's hobbyist-grade stuff that happens to work well when you give it elevation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">LoRa Radio Device</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Options:</strong> RAK WisBlock Meshtastic ($60-80) or Heltec V3 ($25-30)</p>
          <p><strong>What it does:</strong> ESP32-based radio running Meshtastic firmware. 915 MHz, ~100mW output.</p>
          <p><strong>Size:</strong> 2"x3" PCB in small weatherproof case</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Power System</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Solar panel:</strong> 10-20W ($15-30)</p>
          <p><strong>Battery:</strong> 10Ah LiFePO4 or 18650 pack ($20-40)</p>
          <p><strong>Charge controller:</strong> Built into most devices or $10 add-on</p>
          <p><strong>Daily consumption:</strong> ~2-3Wh (router runs continuously)</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Antenna</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Basic:</strong> 5.8 dBi omnidirectional fiberglass ($15-25)</p>
          <p><strong>Better:</strong> 8-10 dBi collinear ($30-50)</p>
          <p><strong>Connector:</strong> SMA or RP-SMA depending on device</p>
          <p><strong>Cable:</strong> Short run LMR-195 or LMR-240 (minimize loss)</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Weatherproofing</h3>
        <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Enclosure:</strong> IP65-rated project box ($10-20) or waterproof case</p>
          <p><strong>Cable entries:</strong> Cable glands ($5)</p>
          <p><strong>Mounting:</strong> Hose clamps, U-bolts, or pole mount kit ($10-15)</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-prairie-gold/10 border border-prairie-gold/30 p-5">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
        <strong>Total cost:</strong> $60-150 depending on which components you choose. This is prosumer hobbyist equipment, not commercial-grade infrastructure.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Installation Process -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Installation process</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        If you're comfortable with basic electronics, you can install it yourself—this is simpler than most amateur radio equipment. Or coordinate with someone local for install help.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">1. Mount the enclosure</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Small weatherproof box (roughly 6"x4"x3") mounts to tower leg or nearby structure using U-bolts or hose clamps.</p>
          <p>Doesn't need to be at absolute top—anywhere with clear view works. Even 20 feet below your repeater antenna is fine.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">2. Install the antenna</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Small omnidirectional antenna (12-24 inches tall) mounts to tower or mast. Run short coax to enclosure.</p>
          <p>Vertical polarization is standard. Keep cable run short (under 10 feet if possible) to minimize loss at 915 MHz.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">3. Mount solar panel</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>10-20W panel (roughly 12"x8") mounts anywhere with southern exposure. Tower leg, nearby structure, whatever works.</p>
          <p>Wiring runs to enclosure. Total draw is minimal—this isn't like powering a repeater.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">4. Configure the device</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Initial setup via Bluetooth from ground level or laptop at site. Set as ROUTER role, configure regional settings (915 MHz US), connect to KC mesh channel.</p>
          <p>Once configured, it runs autonomously. No monitoring required.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">5. Ongoing maintenance</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Check status remotely via mesh. Physical maintenance rarely needed—maybe inspect weatherproofing annually.</p>
          <p>Firmware updates possible over-the-air if needed, but typically it just runs.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- No Interference -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Will this interfere with your repeater?</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>No.</strong> Completely different band.
      </p>
      <p>
        Your repeater operates in VHF/UHF ham bands (typically 144-148 MHz or 420-450 MHz). Meshtastic uses 902-928 MHz ISM band (915 MHz center). Zero overlap, zero interference potential.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's an independent system that happens to share your tower space. No shared feedlines, no duplexer complications, no repeater controller integration. Just a small radio doing its thing 500 MHz away from your operations.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What Success Looks Like -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What success looks like</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>Router 1 (east side)</strong> is currently providing 5-8 mile coverage from a residential roof at maybe 15 feet above surrounding terrain. Not a tower, not even a tall building—just a roof.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Imagine what your tower height could do.</strong> 50 feet? 100 feet? With clear line-of-sight in all directions? You're looking at 15-25+ miles of coverage, potentially more depending on terrain.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>A west-side router is what makes the network actually work.</strong> East + West routers give backbone coverage across the metro. Then client nodes fill in density, and you've got real infrastructure.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Deploy Your Own -->
  <section class="mt-12 text-center">
    <div class="inline-block rounded-3xl bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-blue to-kc-red p-8 text-cream-50 shadow-card md:p-10">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Ready to deploy a router at your site?</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-xl text-base opacity-95">
        Especially if you've got a tower west of State Line Road. You could deploy the router that closes the KC mesh coverage gap.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/community/contact"
        class="mt-6 inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-cream-50 px-8 py-3 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-kc-blue transition hover:bg-surface-200"
      >
        Questions? Let's talk →
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
